==Old English==
===Etymology===
From an Indo-European root ''*skai-, *ski-''.  Cognate with Old High German ''skīnan'' (German [[scheinen]]), Old Saxon ''skīnan'' (Dutch [[schijnen]]), Old Norse ''skína'' (Swedish [[skina]]), Gothic [[𐍃𐌺𐌴𐌹𐌽𐌰𐌽]].  The IE root is also the source of Greek [[σκιά]], Old Slavic ''sěn’'' (Russian [[сень]]).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'ʃi:nan/

===Verb===
'''scīnan''' (class I strong: '''scīneþ'''/'''scīnþ''' ‘it shines’; '''scān''' ‘it shone’; '''scinon''' ‘they shone’; '''ġescinen''' past participle)
# to [[shine]]

